\begin_layout Section
Brief introduction to differential geometry
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Differential Manifolds
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The mathematical language of General Relativity (here from now GR) is the
 differential geometry.
 In this section we are going to give some of the main geometric definitions
 and properties used in GR.
 For further details see Tejeiro.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 be a topological space, a 
\series bold
coordinate chart
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{\alpha}=\left(\varphi_{\alpha},U_{\alpha}\right)$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{\alpha}:U_{\alpha}\subseteq\mathcal{M}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}^{n},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is an open set over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 We call a 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{C^{r}}$
\end_inset

-atlas
\series default
 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 to a chart collection 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ C_{\alpha}=\left(\varphi_{\alpha},U_{\alpha}\right)\right\} _{\alpha\in I}$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{M}=\bigcup_{\alpha\in I}U_{\alpha},
\]

\end_inset

and if 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{\alpha}\bigcap U_{\beta}\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{\beta}\circ\varphi_{\alpha}^{-1}:\varphi_{\alpha}\left(U_{\alpha}\bigcap U_{\beta}\right)\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{n}\rightarrow\varphi_{\beta}\left(U_{\alpha}\bigcap U_{\beta}\right)\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{n}
\]

\end_inset

is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{r}$
\end_inset

 diffeomorfism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{r}$
\end_inset

 atlas over a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 are 
\series bold
compatible
\series default
 if the union of the atlas is a new atlas, then, the union of all compatible
 atlas over a topological space forms an equivalence class atlas, or a maximal
 altas.
 Then, a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{r}$
\end_inset

 differentiable manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is a Haurdorff topological space with a maximal atlas.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A manifold is 
\series bold
orientable
\series default
 if there is an atlas 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \phi_{\alpha},U_{\alpha}\right\} _{\alpha\in I}$
\end_inset

 such that, in every no-empty intersection 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{\alpha}\bigcap U_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 of open sets, the determinant of the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial x^{i}/\partial x'^{j}$
\end_inset

 is greater than zero, where 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{i}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 coordinates and 
\begin_inset Formula $x'^{i}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 coordinates.
 An atlas is 
\series bold
locally finite
\series default
, if every point in the manifold has an open neighborhood that intercepts
 only a finite number of neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{\beta}$
\end_inset

.
 A manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
paracompact
\series default
 if for every atlas 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \phi_{\alpha},U_{\alpha}\right\} _{\alpha\in I}$
\end_inset

, exist a a locally finite atlas 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \psi_{\beta},V_{\beta}\right\} _{\beta\in I}$
\end_inset

 with each 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 contained in some 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Tangent space , Dual space and Tensors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Tangent space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us define the set of all real value functions over a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{F}\left(\mathcal{M},\mathbb{R}\right):=\left\{ f:\mathcal{M}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}\right\} ,
\]

\end_inset

where for 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in\mathcal{F}\left(\mathcal{M},\mathbb{R}\right)$
\end_inset

 we have a vector space structure and if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is differentiable respect to a chart 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\phi_{\alpha},U_{\alpha}\right)$
\end_inset

, it is also differentiable respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\phi_{\beta},U_{\beta}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
tangent vector
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{p}$
\end_inset

 to the manifold in a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is a function
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{cccc}
v_{p}: & \mathcal{F}\left(\mathcal{M},\mathbb{R}\right) & \rightarrow & \mathbb{R}\\
\  & f & \mapsto & v_{p}\left(f\right)
\end{array},
\]

\end_inset

such that 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{p}$
\end_inset

 is lineal in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and meets the Leibniz product property.
 The space of all tangent vectors at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

, is a vector real space.
 The partial derivatives, denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2,...,n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the manifolds dimension, are tanget vectors in 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and form a base for the tangent space.
 Then, for 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{p}\in T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and introducing the Einsten sum convention
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{p}=\left.\sum_{\alpha}v_{p}^{\alpha}\partial_{\alpha}\right|_{p}\equiv\left.v_{p}^{\alpha}\partial_{\alpha}\right|_{p}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Dual space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
one-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}$
\end_inset

 
\series default
in the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is a real function over 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{cccc}
\boldsymbol{\omega}: & T_{p}\mathcal{M} & \rightarrow & \mathbb{R}\\
\  & \boldsymbol{v} & \mapsto & \boldsymbol{\omega}\left(\boldsymbol{v}\right)\equiv\left\langle \boldsymbol{\omega},\boldsymbol{v}\right\rangle 
\end{array},
\]

\end_inset

such that 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}$
\end_inset


\series default
 is linear in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 The space of all one-forms, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}^{*}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

, is called the dual vector space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Every function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{F}\left(\mathcal{M},\mathbb{R}\right)$
\end_inset

 defines a one-form 
\begin_inset Formula $df$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, this one.form is called the 
\series bold
differential
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 For the local coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\alpha}(p)=\left(x^{1},x^{2},...,x^{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 we have that the set of differentials
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\{ dx^{1},dx^{2},...,dx^{n}\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

in 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 forms a base for the dual vector space, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{\omega}=\omega_{\alpha}dx^{\alpha}.
\]

\end_inset

This space meets the condition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle dx^{\alpha},\partial_{\beta}\right\rangle =\delta_{\beta}^{\alpha},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \partial_{\alpha}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is a base of 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Tensors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{r}^{s}$
\end_inset

 be defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pi_{r}^{s}:=\left\{ \left(\boldsymbol{\eta}^{1},...,\boldsymbol{\eta}^{r},\boldsymbol{Y}_{1},...,\boldsymbol{Y}_{s}\right)\text{|}\boldsymbol{\eta}^{i}\in T_{p}^{*}\mathcal{M},\boldsymbol{Y}_{j}\in T_{p}\mathcal{M}\right\} ,
\]

\end_inset

then a 
\series bold
tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{T}$
\end_inset

 of type
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{(r,s)}$
\end_inset

 is a multilinear function over 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{r}^{s}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{cccc}
\boldsymbol{T}: & \Pi_{r}^{s} & \rightarrow & \mathbb{R}\\
\  & \left(\boldsymbol{\eta}^{1},...,\boldsymbol{\eta}^{r},\boldsymbol{Y}_{1},...,\boldsymbol{Y}_{s}\right) & \mapsto & \boldsymbol{T}\left(\boldsymbol{\eta}^{1},...,\boldsymbol{\eta}^{r},\boldsymbol{Y}_{1},...,\boldsymbol{Y}_{s}\right)
\end{array}.
\]

\end_inset

The space of all tensors, denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{s}^{r}$
\end_inset

, is called the tensor product
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{s}^{r}:=\underset{r\text{-times}}{\underbrace{T_{p}\mathcal{M}\otimes\cdots\otimes T_{p}\mathcal{M}}}\otimes\underset{s\text{-times}}{\underbrace{T_{p}^{*}\mathcal{M}\otimes\cdots\otimes T_{p}^{*}\mathcal{M}}},
\]

\end_inset

this is a vector real space of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $r+s$
\end_inset

.
 Given 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{T}\in T_{s}^{r}$
\end_inset

 it can be written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{T}=T_{\beta_{1}\cdots\beta_{s}}^{\alpha_{1}\cdots\alpha_{r}}\partial_{\alpha_{1}}\otimes\cdots\otimes\partial_{\alpha_{r}}\otimes dx^{\beta_{1}}\otimes\cdots\otimes dx^{\beta_{s}},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\beta_{1}\cdots\beta_{s}}^{\alpha_{1}\cdots\alpha_{r}}$
\end_inset

 are the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{T}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Under a change of coordinates the tensor components, the vector and the
 one-foms components as well, transform acording to
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
{T'}{}_{\sigma_{1}\cdots\sigma_{s}}^{\gamma_{1}\cdots\gamma_{r}}=\frac{\partial x'^{\gamma_{1}}}{\partial x{}^{\alpha_{1}}}\cdots\frac{\partial x'{}^{\gamma_{r}}}{\partial x{}^{\alpha_{r}}}\frac{\partial x{}^{\beta_{1}}}{\partial x'{}^{\sigma_{1}}}\cdots\frac{\partial x{}^{\beta_{s}}}{\partial x'{}^{\sigma_{s}}}T_{\beta_{1}\cdots\beta_{s}}^{\alpha_{1}\cdots\alpha_{r}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Transformation between manifolds
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}$
\end_inset

 be two manifolds.
 We can define a diffeomorfism between these manifolds
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi:\mathcal{M}\rightarrow\mathcal{N}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From this, we can induce a new function
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{cccc}
\tilde{\phi}: & \mathcal{F}\left(\mathcal{M}\right) & \rightarrow & \mathcal{F}\left(\mathcal{M}\right)\\
\  & f & \mapsto & \tilde{\phi}\left(f\right)
\end{array}
\]

\end_inset

defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\phi}\left(f\right)=f\left(\phi(p)\right)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 We induce now the function
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{cccc}
\phi_{*}: & T_{p}\mathcal{M} & \rightarrow & T_{\phi(p)}\mathcal{N}\\
\  & \boldsymbol{X} & \mapsto & \phi_{*}\left(\boldsymbol{X}\right)
\end{array}
\]

\end_inset

such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left.\phi_{*}\left(\boldsymbol{X}(f)\right)\right|_{\phi(p)}:=\left.\boldsymbol{X}\left(f\circ\phi\right)\right|_{p},
\]

\end_inset

the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{*}$
\end_inset

 is known as 
\series bold
pushforward
\series default
.
 Now, from the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{*}$
\end_inset

, we define the function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{cccc}
\phi^{*}: & T_{\phi(p)}^{*}\mathcal{N} & \rightarrow & T_{p}^{*}\mathcal{M}\\
\  & \boldsymbol{\omega} & \mapsto & \phi^{*}\left(\boldsymbol{\omega}\right)
\end{array}
\]

\end_inset

given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle \phi^{*}\left(\boldsymbol{\omega}\right),\boldsymbol{X}\right\rangle =\left\langle \boldsymbol{\omega},\phi_{*}\left(\boldsymbol{X}\right)\right\rangle ,
\]

\end_inset

the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{*}$
\end_inset

 is known as 
\series bold
pullback
\series default
.
 These functions extends to tensors of type 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,s)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(r,0)$
\end_inset

, then extends to 
\begin_inset Formula $(r,s)$
\end_inset

 tensors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Curvature
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Connection and covariant derivative
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given the fact that under the change of coordinates de partial derivative
 is not invariant, we need to generalize this concept over a manifold.
 This generalization is given by the 
\series bold
covariant derivative
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\boldsymbol{X}}\boldsymbol{Y}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{X},\boldsymbol{Y}\in T_{p}\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 Because 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\boldsymbol{X}}\boldsymbol{Y}$
\end_inset

 is a tensor, we can write it using the bases 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \partial_{\alpha}\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ dx^{\alpha}\right\} $
\end_inset

, then the components of this tensor, denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{\beta}Y^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

, are
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nabla_{\beta}Y^{\alpha}=\partial_{\beta}Y^{\alpha}+\Gamma_{\beta\gamma}^{\alpha}Y^{\gamma}.
\]

\end_inset

The terms 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{\beta\gamma}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 are called 
\series bold
Christoffel symbols of the second kind
\series default
, these symbols are given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Gamma_{\beta\gamma}^{\alpha}=\left\langle dx^{\alpha},\nabla_{\partial_{\beta}}\partial_{\alpha}\right\rangle .
\]

\end_inset

Just like the partial derivative, it is linear and meets the Leibniz product
 property.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We extend the covariant derivative to arbitrary tensor.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{T}\in T_{r}^{s}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\boldsymbol{T}\in T_{r+1}^{s}$
\end_inset

, where the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\boldsymbol{T}$
\end_inset

 are
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nabla_{\gamma}T_{\beta_{1}\cdots\beta_{s}}^{\alpha_{1}\cdots\alpha_{r}}=\partial_{\gamma}T_{\beta_{1}\cdots\beta_{s}}^{\alpha_{1}\cdots\alpha_{r}}+\Gamma_{\gamma\sigma}^{\alpha_{1}}T_{\beta_{1}\cdots\beta_{s}}^{\sigma\alpha_{2}\cdots\alpha_{r}}+\cdots+\Gamma_{\gamma\sigma}^{\alpha_{r}}T_{\beta_{1}\cdots\beta_{s}}^{\sigma\alpha_{2}\cdots\alpha_{r-1}\sigma}-\Gamma_{\gamma\beta_{1}}^{\sigma}T_{\sigma\beta_{2}\cdots\beta_{s}}^{\alpha_{1}\cdots\alpha_{r}}-\cdots-\Gamma_{\gamma\beta_{s}}^{\sigma}T_{\beta_{1}\cdots\sigma\beta_{s-1}}^{\alpha_{1}\cdots\alpha_{r}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_body
